## Generate Dynamic OpenGraph Images in Next.js

### Overview
OpenGraph images are the thumbnails shown when you share a URL on social media. Next.js ships `next/og` (built on the `satori` library) to generate them on-demand via the Edge Runtime — no canvas, no sharp, no Node.js dependencies.

### 1. Verify no install is needed
- `next/og` ships with Next.js 14+. No additional package needed.
- If you are on Next.js 13, install: `npm install @vercel/og` and import from `@vercel/og` instead.
- For Next.js 14+, always use `import { ImageResponse } from 'next/og'`.

### 2. Create the OG image route
- Create `app/api/og/route.tsx`:
  ```
  import { ImageResponse } from 'next/og';
  import { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

  export const runtime = 'edge';

  export async function GET(request: NextRequest) {
    const { searchParams } = new URL(request.url);
    const title = searchParams.get('title') ?? 'My Website';
    const description = searchParams.get('description') ?? '';

    return new ImageResponse(
      (
        <div
          style={{
            width: '100%',
            height: '100%',
            display: 'flex',
            flexDirection: 'column',
            alignItems: 'center',
            justifyContent: 'center',
            backgroundColor: '#09090b',
            color: 'white',
            fontFamily: 'sans-serif',
            padding: '64px',
          }}
        >
          <h1 style={{ fontSize: 64, fontWeight: 700, margin: 0 }}>{title}</h1>
          {description && (
            <p style={{ fontSize: 32, margin: '16px 0 0', color: '#a1a1aa' }}>
              {description}
            </p>
          )}
        </div>
      ),
      { width: 1200, height: 630 }
    );
  }
  ```
- Standard OG image size is **1200×630 px** — Twitter and most platforms accept this.
- `export const runtime = 'edge'` is required. `ImageResponse` only runs on the Edge Runtime.
- Style with **inline styles only**. Tailwind CSS classes are not supported inside `ImageResponse`.

### 3. Load custom fonts
- Declare the font fetch at module level so it is shared across requests:
  ```
  const fontDataPromise = fetch(
    new URL('/fonts/Inter-Bold.ttf', process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL ?? 'http://localhost:3000')
  ).then((r) => r.arrayBuffer());

  export async function GET(request: NextRequest) {
    const fontData = await fontDataPromise;
    return new ImageResponse(
      (<div style={{ fontFamily: 'Inter' }}>...</div>),
      {
        width: 1200,
        height: 630,
        fonts: [
          { name: 'Inter', data: fontData, style: 'normal', weight: 700 },
        ],
      }
    );
  }
  ```
- Place the font file in `public/fonts/`. Only `.ttf` and `.otf` are supported — `.woff` and `.woff2` do not work with satori.
- To use Google Fonts: fetch from `https://fonts.gstatic.com/s/<path>.ttf`.

### 4. Add OG metadata to pages (site-wide defaults)
- In `app/layout.tsx`:
  ```
  import type { Metadata } from 'next';

  export const metadata: Metadata = {
    metadataBase: new URL(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL ?? 'http://localhost:3000'),
    openGraph: {
      images: [{ url: '/api/og', width: 1200, height: 630, alt: 'My Website' }],
    },
    twitter: {
      card: 'summary_large_image',
      images: ['/api/og'],
    },
  };
  ```
- `metadataBase` is required. Without it, Next.js generates relative URLs and social crawlers ignore them.

### 5. Dynamic OG images per page
- In `app/blog/[slug]/page.tsx`:
  ```
  import type { Metadata } from 'next';

  export async function generateMetadata(
    { params }: { params: { slug: string } }
  ): Promise<Metadata> {
    const post = await getPost(params.slug);
    const base = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL ?? 'http://localhost:3000';
    const ogUrl = new URL('/api/og', base);
    ogUrl.searchParams.set('title', post.title);
    ogUrl.searchParams.set('description', post.excerpt);

    return {
      title: post.title,
      openGraph: {
        title: post.title,
        description: post.excerpt,
        images: [{ url: ogUrl.toString(), width: 1200, height: 630 }],
      },
    };
  }
  ```

### 6. Add response caching
- Cache the generated image in production to avoid regenerating on every visit:
  ```
  return new ImageResponse(jsx, {
    width: 1200,
    height: 630,
    headers: {
      'Cache-Control': 'public, max-age=86400, s-maxage=86400, stale-while-revalidate=604800',
    },
  });
  ```
- On Vercel the Edge Runtime caches automatically via the CDN. The header is still good practice for self-hosted setups.

### 7. Preview locally
- Visit `http://localhost:3000/api/og?title=Hello+World&description=My+description` in your browser — the PNG renders inline.
- After deploying, use opengraph.xyz or metatags.io to see what it looks like in social feeds.
- Clear stale Facebook cache via the Open Graph Debugger (developers.facebook.com/tools/debug/).

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Error: Edge Runtime does not support Node.js 'fs' module`** → The route file imports something that uses Node.js APIs. Keep `app/api/og/route.tsx` to pure JSX + fetch only. Move any data fetching into a separate file that uses `fetch`, not `fs`.
- **`ImageResponse is not a function`** → Wrong import. Use `import { ImageResponse } from 'next/og'`. Do not mix Next.js 14+ imports with the older `@vercel/og` package.
- **Font not rendering / blank text** → Fonts must be `.ttf` or `.otf`. Convert `.woff2` to `.ttf` first. Verify the path resolves at runtime — log `fontData.byteLength` to confirm the fetch succeeded.
- **Image renders blank** → Missing `export const runtime = 'edge'`. The Node.js runtime does not support `ImageResponse`.
- **Inline styles are ignored** → You used Tailwind classes. Use plain inline `style={{}}` objects. `twc` or other CSS-in-JS does not work here.
- **OG image not showing in social preview** → `metadataBase` is missing in `app/layout.tsx`. Without an absolute base URL, the `og:image` meta tag contains a relative path that crawlers reject.
- **`ERR_NAME_NOT_RESOLVED` during font fetch** → `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL` is undefined locally. Add `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL=http://localhost:3000` to `.env.local`.
- **Different image per page not working** → Ensure `generateMetadata` returns a new `ogUrl` with `searchParams.set(...)` per page. Verify `metadataBase` is set so the URL is absolute in the HTML head.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT use Tailwind CSS classes inside `ImageResponse` JSX — satori only understands a subset of inline CSS.
- Do NOT import Node.js-only modules (`fs`, `path`, `sharp`, `canvas`) — the Edge Runtime only supports web-standard APIs (`fetch`, `URL`, `crypto`, etc.).
- Do NOT use `.woff` or `.woff2` font files — only `.ttf` / `.otf` work with satori's text renderer.
- Do NOT skip `metadataBase` in `layout.tsx` — the og:image URL must be absolute or social platforms will ignore it.
- Do NOT fetch the font inside the request handler without memoizing — this causes a new HTTP request per image generation and adds latency. Fetch the font at module scope so it is shared.
- Do NOT use `<img>` tags inside the JSX for local assets without an absolute URL — use `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL` to build the URL.
- Do NOT try to use `next/image` (`<Image>`) inside `ImageResponse` — it is not supported. Use a plain `<img>` tag with an absolute URL instead.
